{{Quote|You don't know how much you don't know until you get here.|Leland Chee|<ref name="Wired">{{WebCite|url=https://www.wired.com/2008/08/ff-starwarscanon|text=Meet Leland Chee, the Star Wars Franchise Continuity Cop|author=Baker, Chris|date=2008-08-18|work=[[Wikipedia:Wired (magazine)|Wired]]|archivedate=20220121165117}}</ref>}}
The '''Holocron continuity database''' is the database used internally by [[Lucas Licensing]] to keep track of all of the fictional elements created for the ''[[Star Wars]]'' universe. It is maintained by [[Leland Chee]]<ref name="What is">{{SW|url=news/what-is-the-holocron|text=What is the Holocron?}}</ref> on [[Wikipedia:FileMaker Pro|FileMaker Pro]] software,<ref name="Wired" /> and was created in January 2000,<ref name="What is" /> initially to support the new ''Star Wars'' roleplaying game being created by Wizards of the Coast. Starting from a core of material imported into the database from the ''[[Behind the Magic]]'' CD-ROM, it has since grown substantially as new information has been added.<ref name="FrenchInterview">{{WebCite|url=https://www.starwars-universe.com/dossier-page-145-984-leland-chee-responsable-de-la-continuite.html|text=Leland Chee : responsable de la continuité|date=2009-05-06|work=Starwars-Universe.com|language=French and English|quote=The Holocron is a database of Star Wars lore with over 36,000 entries containing information on every character, creature, planet, vehicle, weapon, created for the Star Wars universe.|archivedate=20160109125317}}</ref>

==History {{SectionFlag}}==
The first article, titled "Welcome to the Holocron!", was created on [[February 9]], [[2000]],<ref name="Instagram 20 Years">{{Instagram|username=holocronkeeper|url=p/B8WeUK-A6nJ|name=[[Leland Chee|Leland Y Chee]]|archivefile=File:Holocron-database-anniversary.png}}</ref> and 22 years later, the Holocron reached the major milestone of 100,000 entries, on [[February 16]], [[2022]].<ref name="Twitter3">{{Twitter|HolocronKeeper|status/1493769741328134144|[[Leland Chee]]|quote=Just entered my 100,000th Holocron entry.|archivedate=20220216072318}}</ref> One of the entries is about the band [[Jefferson Starship]], who were featured within the ''[[The Star Wars Holiday Special]]''.<ref name="Chee Jefferson">{{Bluesky|holocronkeeper.bsky.social|post/3lb6oe4xmp22m|[[Leland Chee]]|date=2024-11-17|quote=Of course it does! {{C|In respone to: "Do Jefferson Starship have an entry on the Holocron?"?}}|archiveurl=https://archive.ph/Z2Kzl}}</ref> As of [[February 3]], [[2026]], the Holocron had 120,000 entries.<ref name="HolocronEntries2026">{{WookDiscord|discordname=.holocronkeeper|name=Leland Chee|date=2026-02-03|messagelink=https://discord.com/channels/397848917036761090/1001634661216301078/1468324815986491609|quote=ENTRIES: 120,000 SOURCES: 3,550 IMAGES: 34,547 CHARACTERS; 39,764 PLANETS; 8,141 ALIENS: 1,851 CREATURES: 3,501 VEHICLE TYPES    : 4,021 WEAPONS: 4,714 GROUPS: 8,720|archivefile=File:Holocron-database-2026-Stats.png}} {{C|In response to: "Hi Leland. Sorry to bother you but I am very interested in the Holocron continuity database. In 2022, you posted statistics on your Instagram about the Holocron entry counts. Could you share those same statistics again? Also, I know both the current canon and Legends entries exist in the Holocron. How many are there for each? Finally, I really appreciate that your long-time work as Keeper of the Holocron."}}</ref>

According to Chee, before the creation of the Holocron, Lucasfilm kept track of continuity physically on black binders, internally nicknamed the "Star Wars Bible."<ref name="FrenchInterview" />

There are no plans to release any portion of the Holocron to the public. One reason cited by Chee is:
{{Quote|In addition to being an archive for information that has already been published, the Holocron is a tool to track everything that is currently in development. Information is entered at the earliest stages, so there is information about products that won't be released until years later. It is also used to store unpublished reference information.|Leland Chee|<ref name="Blog4">{{Blog|holocron|4|What is the Holocron?}}</ref>}}
A rare glimpse at the Holocron was seen at the [[Celebration IV]] "30 Years of Star Wars Publishing and Continuity" panel.<ref name="Blog-holocron 39">{{Blog|holocron|39|Celebration IV Continuity Panel}}</ref> At [[Celebration Anaheim (2015)|Celebration Anaheim]] in [[2015]], Chee reiterated that Lucas Licensing will never make the Holocron public, because it includes forthcoming content.<ref name="Second Chee Reason, from Anaheim">{{SWYouTube|lNVfsIkLm0M|Pablo Hidalgo and Leland Chee Interview with StarWars.com &#124; Star Wars Celebration Anaheim|sw_url=video/pablo-hidalgo-and-leland-chee-interview-star-wars-celebration-anaheim}}</ref>

According to Chee, the Holocron continuity database provides services to all departments within Lucasfilm, it does not belong to any specific department.<ref name="Holocron department">{{WookDiscord|discordname=.holocronkeeper|name=Leland Chee|date=2025-04-04|messagelink=https://discord.com/channels/397848917036761090/492458000720592906/1357743103536005251|quote=Our team provides services to every department in the company so I wouldn’t really say the Holocron falls under any one department. What I will say is that the bulk of my day-to-day is games, books, consumer products, digital, and LEGO. Others on the team allocate their time differently.|archivefile=File:LelandChee-Holocron-department-Discord.png}}</ref>

==Data model {{SectionFlag}}==
Fields for entries in the database include "Keywords," "Era of influence" (e.g., "the New Republic"), "Classification" (e.g., "location"), "Subtype" (e.g., "System:planet", "Vehicle Type:speeder", "Device:Medical", "Slang:Curse", "Alien:Mammalian"), "Brief description," "Size," and "Special abilities." [[Alien]]-specific fields include "Diet" and "Disposition," and for organizations, "Goals," though these are not used often. For astronomical objects, information for region, sector, system, and grid coordinates is tracked. Over time, fields like foreign language translation and timeline have become obsolete, replaced with other systems. Continuity-related fields such as "[[Star Wars Legends|Legends]]," "[[LEGO]]/[[Star Wars: Visions|Visions]]" are also used.<ref name="Fields">{{Bluesky|chronokeeper.bsky.social|post/3l5e5wdxxha22|ChronoKeeper|date=2024-09-30|archivedate=20251118212609}}</ref>

The Holocron also includes a phonetic pronunciation key for names.<ref name="pronunciation key">{{Instagram|username=holocronkeeper|url=p/DK3sLbOOY4g|name=Holocron Phonetic Pronunciation Key|date=2025-06-25|quote=Stephen Stanton just shared a post describing how they maintained a level of consistency with pronunciations for Star Wars Rebels and I figure I’d shared this guide to the phonetic spellings I use in the Holocron.|archiveurl=https://archive.is/BgTdG}}</ref>

